%section.how-to#HowToInstall
  %h2 How To Install
  %p Installing Cylon.js with leapmotion support is pretty easy.
  :markdown
        :::bash
        npm install cylon-leapmotion
  %p
    In order to use this module , you need to install the drivers/software from the Leapmotion site
    =link_to "https://www.leapmotion.com/setup", "https://www.leapmotion.com/setup"
    , make sure that is installed before use the commands and events (and SDK too if you want, but the SDK is not needed for cylon.js).


%section.how-to#HowToUse
  %h2 How To Use
  %p This small program uses a Leap Motion to detect the user's hand position
  :markdown
        :::javascript
        var Cylon = require('cylon');

        Cylon.robot({
          connection: {
            name: 'leapmotion',
            adaptor: 'leapmotion',
            port: '127.0.0.1:6437'
          },

          device: {
            name: 'leapmotion',
            driver: 'leapmotion'
          },

          work: function(my) {
            my.leapmotion.on('hand', function(payload) {
              Logger.info(payload.toString());
            });
          }
        }).start();


%section.how-to#HowToConnect
  %h2 How To Connect
  %h3 OSX
  %p
    This driver works out of the box with the vanilla installation of the Leap Motion Software that you get in their
    =link_to "Setup Guide." ,"https://www.leapmotion.com/setup"

  %p The main steps are:

  %ul
    %li Run Leap Motion.app to open a websocket connection in port 6437.
    %li Connect your Computer and Leap Motion Controller.
    %li Connect to the device via Cylon.js.

  %h3 Ubuntu
  %p
    The Linux download of the Leap Motion software can be obtained from
    =link_to "Leap Motion Dev Center", "https://developer.leapmotion.com/downloads"
    (requires free signup)
  %p The main steps are:
  %ul
    %li Run the leapd daemon to open a websocket connection in port 6437.
    %li Connect your computer and the Leap Motion controller
    %li Connect to the device via Cylon.js

